\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 4. M. brasiliense} Camb. in St-Hil.,{\i  Fl. Bras. Mer.}{\b  2}: 252 (1830). Stems up to 200 cm, often woody at base. Leaves 4-6 in a whorl, usually longer than internodes; emergent leaves light blue-green, covered by minute, transparent, hemispherical glands; segments 8-30. Flowers unisexual, solitary, axillary; bracts pinnatisect, resembling foliage leaves. Petals 5 mm in male flowers, absent in female. Stamens 8. Fruit 1·8 × 1·2 mm, ovoid, finely tuberculate. {\i Cultivated for ornament and locally naturalized in S.W. France; frequently casual elsewhere in Europe.} [Ga.] ({\i Tropical and subtropical South America}.)
\par

